---

## Critical Safety Rules

```text
1. Never delete source code without a backup or git checkpoint.
2. Never expose real secrets in logs, commits, reports, screenshots, or terminal output.
3. Never hardcode production passwords, provider keys, tunnel credentials, bot secrets, JWT secrets, or database credentials.
4. Generate local database passwords with cryptographic randomness.
5. Store generated local secrets only in gitignored env files.
6. Do not remove Docker volumes by default.
7. Do not remove active project data.
8. Inspect before changing files.
9. Prefer env variables and .env.example templates over hardcoded values.
10. Prefer scripts that can be re-run safely.
11. Every change must have a verification command.
12. Stop before destructive operations that may affect user data.
13. For non-destructive issues, make the safest best-effort fix and document it.
14. Do not force push.
15. Keep no-cost guardrails enabled unless explicitly changed by the repository owner.
```

